Consider the case where one writes a general purpose (non-FUSE) in-memory file system:
```go
type Directory struct {
    ...
}
// Functions that have a non-FUSE 'native' API.
func (d *Directory) Mkdir(name string) error { ... }
...
```
And one decides to expose this file system through FUSE as well. Because Go doesn't support function name overloading or Rust-style traits, you end up with the problem that you can't let Directory implement fs.NodeMkdirer due to naming collisions. To solve this you decide to implement a separate adapter-like type with the FUSE methods:
```go
type DirectoryFUSENode struct {
    d *Directory
}
// Functions that have a go-fuse API.
func (d *DirectoryFUSENode) Mkdir(ctx context.Context, name string, mode uint32, out *fuse.EntryOut) (*fs.Inode, syscall.Errno) { ... }
```
Because there should only be up to one fs.Inode per Directory, and because Directory likely needs to call into fs.Inode to do things like invalidation, you decide to embed fs.Inode in Directory:
```go
type Directory struct {
    fuseInode fs.Inode
    ...
}
```
This should be all right, as long as DirectoryFUSENode still implements fs.InodeEmbedder. But here's the problem: fs.InodeEmbedder contains an unexported method named embed(). [This means the interface can only be satisfied by using anonymous structure fields.](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26181271/is-it-possible-to-implement-an-interface-with-unexported-methods-in-another-pack)

Considering that `embed()` does exactly the same thing as `EmbeddedInode()`, would it make sense to eliminate it entirely?

