First of all, thanks for this awesome project! I'm currently debugging an issue I found with gocryptfs (which uses go-fuse) on macOS, and I hope its okay to open a bug report here to get some more opinions involved. The bug is https://github.com/rfjakob/gocryptfs/issues/351, however, I will provide a short summary/analysis below.

The issue occurs in a test that repeatedly creates files and queries directory listings with multiple FUSE systems mounted on top of each other. While this test works fine on Linux, on macOS apparently at some point the directory listings contain outdated information. The exact timing of the failure is more or less random. Looking at the debug output shows that, at the point where the application calls `OpenDir`, there is no corresponding FUSE call. Instead, the following `ReadDir` calls use an existing file handle?!

Relevant log (shortened and annotated):

```
2019/01/15 12:02:45 rx 2: OPENDIR i1 
2019/01/15 12:02:45 tx 2:     OK, {Fh 2 }

    ... file is created here ...

2019/01/15 12:02:45 rx 4: LOOKUP i1 ["gocryptfs.longname.iNPx_rqvgCZCkSHiDxThVRUMDqfqDYPSMcu58uAVTdA"] 63b
2019/01/15 12:02:45 tx 4:     OK, {i330 g329 tE=1s tA=1s {M0100644 SZ=0 L=1 503:204 0 0:3182331 A 1547582565.000000 M 1547582565.000000 C 1547582565.000000}}
[...]
2019/01/15 12:02:45 rx 4: OPEN i330 {O_RDONLY} 
2019/01/15 12:02:45 tx 4:     OK, {Fh 3 }
[...]
2019/01/15 12:02:45 rx 2: RELEASE i330 {Fh 3   L0} 
2019/01/15 12:02:45 tx 2:     OK

    ... opening the file seems to work fine ...
    ... here is an OpenDir call in the source, but there is no matching OPENDIR fuse call ...

2019/01/15 12:02:45 rx 3: READDIR i1 {Fh 2 [0 +6553) } 
2019/01/15 12:02:45 tx 3:     OK,  328b data "\u038d0\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00"...
2019/01/15 12:02:45 rx 2: READDIR i1 {Fh 2 [6 +6553) } 
2019/01/15 12:02:45 tx 2:     OK

    ... unsurprisingly the application gets the outdated directory listing ...
```

Full log is available [here](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/slackner/ca6a69b8886faf9fba3fafd32d7e2f5c/raw/0f5e117898f6d4189a76ce95739a43a02f0b1af1/gistfile1.txt), however it is difficult to read since multiple logs are interleaved.

This gave me the suspicion that the kernel reuses an existing Fh that has been opened, but never read from. To verify this hypothesis, I tried removing the `d.lastOffset > 0` condition in `fuse/nodefs/dir.go`, and it indeed fixed the issue:

```
	// rewinddir() should be as if reopening directory.
	// TODO - test this.
	if d.lastOffset > 0 && input.Offset == 0 {
		d.stream, code = d.node.OpenDir((*fuse.Context)(&input.Context))
		if !code.Ok() {
			return code
		}
	}
```

I know that we are now querying the directory content twice, but for a short demonstration it should be sufficient. A comparison with `libfuse` confirms that this is also what the C-implementations do.

Linux: https://github.com/libfuse/libfuse/blob/b8093eb57b5cf71dbe91dcb5cf5f8c86b1641752/lib/fuse.c#L3703
MacOS: https://github.com/osxfuse/fuse/blob/abc35f85fdede186ed164082bd71fc1217d2f58f/lib/fuse.c#L3983

In both cases, the code states that:

```
	/* According to SUS, directory contents need to be refreshed on
	   rewinddir() */
	if (!off)
		dh->filled = 0;

	if (!dh->filled) {
		err = readdir_fill(f, req, ino, size, off, dh, &fi, flags);
```

I suspect `go-fuse` should behave in the same way and needs to drop the whole `d.lastOffset` tracking. What else could be done to track this problem down further?

Probably no longer relevant then after fixing this bug, but I also stumpled upon the following lines in `fuse/nodefs/dir.go` where the `d.lastOffset` update seems to be missing.

```
		// No need to fill attributes for . and ..
		if e.Name == "." || e.Name == ".." {
			continue
		}
```
**Edit:** If it matters, I'm currently testing on macOS High Sierra with kernel version `17.7.0`.  Osxfuse is at version `3.8.3` and `go-fuse` is at 425e8d5301f6ca119f7abfe798920dbf24a396c7.

- use tA=...s instead of `A...` or `AttrValid=...` for time(Attr valid);
- use tE=...s instead of `EntryValid` for time(Entry valid);
- use iX instead of `NodeId: X` for inode X;
- use gX instead of `Generation=X` for generation X;
- use `[<off> +<size>)` instead of `off <off> sz <sz>`;

- use

	< uniq: iX.Op opargs
	> uniq: status reply...

  instead of

	Dispatch uniq: Op NodeId: X opargs
	Serialize uniq: Op code: status reply...

  for received/replied messages;

- use `["file1", "file2"]` instead of `names: [file1, file2]` for filenames.

- use `xb` instead of `x bytes`

- for replied data, also log data content, but only up to first 8 bytes.
  This does not flood the log, but at the same time makes filesystem
  diagnostics easier.

  If this last change is controversial, it could be dropped from the
  patch.

